cs.IT, cs.DS, cs.NA, cs.SI, cs.CG. 

The paper discusses the construction and analysis of sparse random matrices, which are commonly used in compressed sensing. Therefore, cs.IT (Information Theory) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also discusses expander graphs, which are important in computer science and mathematics, and their connection to the sparse random matrices. This makes cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.CG (Computational Geometry) likely sub-categories. The paper also presents tail bounds on the probability of the cardinality of the set of neighbors for these graphs, which involves probabilistic analysis, making cs.NA (Numerical Analysis) a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses applications to compressed sensing, which falls under cs.SI (Signal Processing).
